# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS crossterm AND WHY IS IT THE 46TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# crossterm (https://github.com/crossterm-rs/crossterm, 4070+ stars)
# is **Timon Post's "Cross platform terminal library rust"** — a
# pure-Rust terminal manipulation library that ABSTRACTS Unix ANSI
# escape sequences AND Windows Console API behind a unified Rust
# interface.  Created in 2017 by Timon Post as a successor to
# termion (which was Unix-only by design), crossterm has become the
# DE FACTO Rust terminal-manipulation library since 2019 — adopted
# as ratatui's default backend (replacing tui-rs's earlier termion-
# default choice).
#
# crossterm's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. CROSS-PLATFORM UNIX + WINDOWS — crossterm is the FIRST
#      Rust terminal library to support BOTH:
#         - Linux + macOS + BSD: ANSI escape sequences
#         - Windows pre-10: Windows Console API
#                            (SetConsoleTextAttribute,
#                             ReadConsoleInput,
#                             GetConsoleScreenBufferInfo)
#         - Windows 10+: VT-mode ANSI (with auto-fallback to
#                         Windows Console API for older Win10 builds)
#      Compare:
#         * termion R550:    Unix-only (pure-Rust ANSI)
#         * termcolor R546:  Unix-ANSI + Windows-Console-API but
#                              ONLY for color (not full terminal
#                              control)
#         * crossterm:        FULL terminal control (color +
#                              cursor + events + screen) across
#                              both platforms
#      FIRST documented Rust terminal library with FULL CROSS-
#      PLATFORM (Unix + Windows) terminal-manipulation support.
#
#   2. execute! / queue! MACRO COMMAND QUEUEING — crossterm uses
#      `execute!` (apply immediately) and `queue!` (batch then
#      flush) macros for terminal commands:
#
#          use std::io::{stdout, Write};
#          use crossterm::{execute, queue, terminal, cursor, style};
#
#          execute!(stdout(),
#              terminal::Clear(terminal::ClearType::All),
#              cursor::MoveTo(10, 5),
#              style::SetForegroundColor(style::Color::Red),
#              style::Print("Hello"),
#              style::ResetColor)?;
#
#          // Or batch via queue!:
#          let mut out = stdout();
#          queue!(out, cursor::MoveTo(10, 5))?;
#          queue!(out, style::Print("Hello"))?;
#          out.flush()?;
#
#      Each command is a Rust struct (`MoveTo(x, y)`,
#      `SetForegroundColor(color)`, `Print(string)`) that
#      implements the Command trait.  execute! / queue! macros
#      pass commands to the writer's `.execute()` or `.queue()`
#      methods.  Compare:
#         * termion R550:  type-Display escape codes via write!()
#         * tcell R551 (Go): SetContent per-cell on a buffer
#         * terminal-kit (TS): chained .moveTo(x,y).bold('text')
#      FIRST documented Rust terminal library with execute!/queue!
#      macro-based command queueing.
#
#   3. POLL-BASED EVENT TIMEOUT — crossterm exposes events through
#      a poll-with-timeout function:
#
#          use crossterm::event::{poll, read, Event, KeyCode, KeyEvent};
#          use std::time::Duration;
#
#          terminal::enable_raw_mode()?;
#          loop {
#              if poll(Duration::from_millis(100))? {
#                  match read()? {
#                      Event::Key(KeyEvent {
#                          code: KeyCode::Char('q'), .. }) => break,
#                      Event::Mouse(me) => { /* mouse event */ }
#                      Event::Resize(c, r) => { /* terminal resize */ }
#                      Event::Paste(s) => { /* bracketed paste */ }
#                      Event::FocusGained => { ... }
#                      Event::FocusLost => { ... }
#                      _ => { ... }
#                  }
#              } else {
#                  /* no events within timeout, do background work */
#              }
#          }
#          terminal::disable_raw_mode()?;
#
#      The `event::poll(Duration)` returns Ok(true) if an event is
#      available within the timeout, false otherwise.  This lets
#      apps multiplex event handling with background work without
#      threads — essential for 60fps game loops like tetro-tui's
#      gravity-based piece-drop timer.  Compare:
#         * termion R550:  stdin.keys() iterator (blocking)
#         * tcell R551 (Go): PollEvent() (blocking)
#         * terminal-kit (TS): on('key', ...) EventEmitter
#      FIRST documented Rust terminal library with poll-with-
#      timeout event handling.
#
#   4. ENUM-BASED COLOR + STYLE WITH THREE PARALLEL APIs —
#      crossterm exposes colors and attributes as Rust enums (not
#      method-chain or escape codes):
#
#          use crossterm::style::{Color, Attribute, Stylize};
#
#          // Three ways to set color/attrs in crossterm:
#          // 1. Enum + execute! macro
#          execute!(stdout(),
#              style::SetForegroundColor(Color::Red),
#              style::SetAttribute(Attribute::Bold))?;
#
#          // 2. Stylize trait extension on &str
#          let styled = "Hello".red().bold();
#          println!("{}", styled);
#
#          // 3. Direct print with style helpers
#          println!("{}", "Hello".with(Color::Red).bold());
#
#      The Color enum supports:
#         * 16 named ANSI colors (Black, Red, Green, ..., Grey,
#           DarkGrey, ..., White)
#         * Ansi256(u8) — 256-color palette
#         * Rgb { r, g, b } — 24-bit truecolor
#      Compare:
#         * termcolor R546: ColorSpec builder applied via
#                            set_color (one API)
#         * termion R550:   color::Red type implementing Display
#                            (one API)
#         * owo-colors R526: trait extension methods (one API)
#         * fatih/color R527 (Go): attribute constants (one API)
#         * chalk R528 (TS):  chained property access (one API)
#         * kleur R548 (TS): method-call chains (one API)
#      FIRST documented Rust terminal library with THREE PARALLEL
#      color/style APIs (enum + Stylize trait + with() method)
#      from a single library.
#
#   5. RATATUI DEFAULT BACKEND — crossterm is the DEFAULT BACKEND
#      for ratatui R530 (the most popular Rust TUI framework).
#      When you `cargo add ratatui` without specifying features,
#      you get crossterm as the implicit dependency.  Hundreds of
#      Rust TUI applications transitively depend on crossterm via
#      ratatui.  Compare:
#         * termion R550:  was tui-rs's original default backend
#                            (ratatui's predecessor); now optional
#                            via ratatui feature flags
#         * crossterm:      ratatui's default (most-used)
#         * termwiz:         wezterm's terminal library, optional
#                            ratatui backend
#      FIRST documented Rust terminal library that's the default
#      backend of a major Rust TUI framework.
#
# crossterm's relationship to other documented Rust CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like termion R550   — low-level terminal-primitives layer
#   * Like termcolor R546 — Windows Console API support (but
#                            crossterm covers full terminal control,
#                            termcolor only colors)
#   * Like ratatui R530   — crossterm is ratatui's default backend
#   * Like cursive R538   — crossterm is one of cursive's 5
#                            backends
#   * Unlike all of the above — CROSS-PLATFORM (Unix + Windows
#                                Console API) + COMPLETE primitives
#                                + execute!/queue! macros + enum-
#                                based colors + ratatui-default-
#                                backend status
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go:      tcell R551 (similar cross-platform low-level
#                                  cell library)
#         * TS-Node: terminal-kit R552 (comprehensive terminal
#                                          utilities)
#     crossterm completes Rust's LOW-LEVEL TERMINAL LIBRARY
#     coverage at TWO libraries (termion + crossterm), giving
#     Rust the BROADEST low-level coverage of any documented
#     language.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE tetro-tui CLI — clap derive + crossterm Composition
#
# tetro-tui's argv parser is clap 4 derive Parser with minimal
# flags (the game is mostly TUI-driven):
#
#     use clap::Parser;
#     #[derive(Parser, Debug)]
#     #[command(version, about, long_about = None)]
#     struct Args {
#         /// Initial seed upon starting a custom game.
#         #[arg(short, long)]
#         seed: Option<u64>,
#
#         /// Initial board upon starting a custom game.
#         #[arg(short, long)]
#         board: Option<String>,
#     }
#     let args = Args::parse();
#
# Two flags — seed and board — for replicating specific game
# starting conditions.  Everything else (game mode selection,
# theme, key bindings, hold piece, gravity speed) happens inside
# the crossterm-driven TUI.
#
# Distinct from every other documented Rust CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. CROSS-PLATFORM UNIX + WINDOWS — Every other documented
#      Rust terminal library is either Unix-only (termion R550)
#      or color-only with Windows support (termcolor R546).
#      crossterm provides FULL terminal control on both Unix and
#      Windows.  FIRST documented Rust full-cross-platform
#      terminal-manipulation library.
#
#   2. execute! / queue! MACRO COMMAND QUEUEING — Every other
#      documented Rust terminal library uses write! macros with
#      Display escape codes (termion R550), set_color builders
#      (termcolor R546), or per-cell SetContent (cursive's
#      backend).  crossterm uses execute!/queue! macros for
#      command batching.  FIRST documented Rust terminal library
#      with execute!/queue! macro-based command queueing.
#
#   3. POLL-BASED EVENT TIMEOUT — Every other documented Rust
#      terminal library uses blocking event readers (termion's
#      stdin.keys()) or callback registration (cursive).
#      crossterm's event::poll(Duration) returns Ok(true) if event
#      available within timeout, enabling event/background-work
#      multiplexing without threads.  FIRST documented Rust
#      terminal library with poll-with-timeout event handling.
#
#   4. THREE-API ENUM + Stylize + with() COLOR — Every other
#      documented Rust terminal library has ONE color API per
#      library.  crossterm provides THREE: Color enum via
#      SetForegroundColor command, Stylize trait extension on
#      strings, and with() method on styled values.  FIRST
#      documented Rust terminal library with three parallel
#      color/style APIs.
#
#   5. RATATUI DEFAULT BACKEND — Every other documented Rust
#      terminal library is either independent (termion R550) or
#      one-of-many backends (cursive's 5 backends).  crossterm is
#      the IMPLICIT-DEFAULT backend for ratatui (used by hundreds
#      of Rust TUI applications transitively).  FIRST documented
#      Rust terminal library that's the default backend of a
#      major Rust TUI framework.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/Strophox/tetro-tui/blob/main/src/main.rs
# clap derive Args struct.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help and exit]' \
    '(-V --version)'{-V,--version}'[print version and exit]' \
    '(-s --seed)'{-s+,--seed=}'[initial 64-bit RNG seed for custom game (deterministic piece sequence)]:seed:' \
    '(-b --board)'{-b+,--board=}'[initial board encoded as character string (e.g. "###/   #")]:board:' \
    && ret=0

return ret
